    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/model-generalization-assessment-across-molecular-size-regimes/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The left panel of Figure 2 shows in red the structure elucidation accuracy of the spectrum-to-structure multitask model as a function of the number of heavy atoms. In comparison to the substructure-to-structure model, there is a more systematic decrease in accuracy with the size of the molecule, decreasing from 77.5% at 10 heavy atoms to 52.0% at 19 heavy atoms.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper does evaluate accuracy across molecular size regimes (10\u201319 heavy atoms), but does NOT explicitly test generalization to molecules OUTSIDE the training scope (i.e., >19 heavy atoms). The paper acknowledges this limitation: 'GDB-17 only contains molecules with up to 17 heavy atoms' and notes that accuracy drops for 18\u201319 heavy atoms due to underrepresentation in training data. The card's framing of 'out-of-scope' (beyond 19 atoms) is not directly validated in the paper.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10_1021_acscentsci_4c01132",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "model-generalization-assessment-across-molecular-size-regimes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "This skill assesses whether a trained structure-prediction model maintains accuracy when applied to molecules outside its training scope, specifically testing generalization across molecular size regimes.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T10:02:38.155472+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/model-generalization-assessment-across-molecular-size-regimes/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "we demonstrate the effectiveness of this framework on molecules with up to 19 heavy (non-hydrogen) atoms, a size for which there are trillions of possible structures.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper trains and evaluates on molecules up to 19 heavy atoms, but does NOT test on molecules larger than 19 atoms. The scope description implies testing on 'larger or smaller molecules' but the paper only addresses the 10\u201319 atom range. Testing on molecules >19 atoms is mentioned as future work, not demonstrated.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10_1021_acscentsci_4c01132",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "model-generalization-assessment-across-molecular-size-regimes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Apply this skill when a deep learning model for molecular structure prediction (e.g., NMR2Struct) has been trained and evaluated on a limited molecular size range (e.g., up to 19 heavy atoms), and you need to determine whether predictions remain reliable for larger or smaller mol",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
