      "asbval:target_claim_field": "expected_outputs",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "quantifies performance degradation and failure modes when the model encounters out-of-scope inputs, establishing empirical boundaries on model applicability",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T10:02:38.155472+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/molecular-fragment-assembly-from-transformer-predictions/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Here, we treat the substructure-to-structure problem as a language translation problem, where we translate a sequence of substructures into a sequence of tokens that can be combined to form a molecule's SMILES string, recovering the molecular connectivity... Autoregressive transformer models have been shown to excel at translation tasks owing to the strong inductive bias provided by the multihead attention mechanism... Here, we adapt a full encoder-decoder transformer architecture for the substructure-to-structure task.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper does use a transformer for assembling fragments (substructures) into molecular structures. However, the claim frames this as 'decoding stage' converting 'fragment embeddings into valid molecular graphs,' which is imprecise. The paper's transformer takes a BINARY VECTOR of substructure presence/absence (not embeddings) and generates SMILES strings token-by-token. The multitask model integrates CNN (for spectral encoding) + transformer (for structure generation), but the transformer's input in the full pipeline is not 'fragment embeddings' but rather spectral features processed through CNN + substructure predictions. The transformer generates SMILES (a sequence representation), not a 'molecular graph' directly.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10_1021_acscentsci_4c01132",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "molecular-fragment-assembly-from-transformer-predictions",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "This skill uses a transformer architecture to assemble large numbers of molecular fragments predicted from spectral features into complete molecular structures with connectivity information. It is applied as the decoding stage of an end-to-end NMR-to-structure pipeline to convert",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T10:02:55.256980+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/molecular-fragment-assembly-from-transformer-predictions/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "For training and testing the spectrum-to-structure model, we used 1H and/or 13C NMR spectra for the \u223c143 thousand set of molecules from SpectraBase predicted using MestreNova... During training, we passed the processed 1H NMR spectra through a one-dimensional convolutional neural network (CNN) to downsample the signal into a lower-dimensional space... These features were then passed through a full encoder-decoder transformer for structure elucidation, which outputs SMILES strings, and a transformer encoder for substructure elucidation, which outputs substructure probability arrays.",
      "asbval:note": "The scope correctly identifies the \u226419 heavy atom limit and the use of CNN + transformer on 1D NMR spectra. However, the phrasing 'a set of candidate molecular fragments predicted for a molecule' is misleading. The paper does not pre-compute a fixed set of candidate fragments; instead, the multitask model jointly predicts substructure probabilities AND structure in an end-to-end fashion. The transformer does not receive 'candidate fragments' as discrete input; it receives spectral features and generates SMILES directly. The substructure predictions are outputs, not inputs to the transformer decoding stage.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10_1021_acscentsci_4c01132",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "molecular-fragment-assembly-from-transformer-predictions",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "When you have encoded spectral features (from a CNN featurizer applied to 1D 1H and/or 13C NMR spectra) and a set of candidate molecular fragments predicted for a molecule with \u226419 heavy atoms, and you need to determine the correct connectivity and assembly order to recover the g",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T10:02:55.256980+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/molecular-fragment-assembly-from-transformer-predictions/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Here, we adapt a full encoder-decoder transformer architecture for the substructure-to-structure task... These features were then passed through a full encoder-decoder transformer for structure elucidation, which outputs SMILES strings",
      "asbval:note": "Transformer architecture is explicitly used and named throughout the paper.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10_1021_acscentsci_4c01132",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "molecular-fragment-assembly-from-transformer-predictions",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools[0].name",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "transformer architecture",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T10:02:55.256980+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/molecular-fragment-assembly-from-transformer-predictions/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Autoregressive transformer models have been shown to excel at translation tasks owing to the strong inductive bias provided by the multihead attention mechanism, which captures global correlations and uses that information to generate the target sequence in a conditioned manner... The inputs to the substructure-to-structure transformer are a binary vector with each entry corresponding to the presence or absence of a specific substructure and a start token. Using only this information, the transformer generates a SMILES string token by token",
      "asbval:note": "The transformer does use attention-based mechanisms and generates molecular connectivity (via SMILES). However, the role description conflates two different transformer uses: (1) substructure-to-structure transformer (takes binary substructure vector, outputs SMILES) and (2) the transformer within the multitask model (takes CNN-encoded spectral features, outputs SMILES). The claim says 'decoding stage for assembling molecular fragments' and 'bond predictions and fragment ordering,' but the paper's transformer generates SMILES tokens sequentially, not explicit bond predictions or fragment ordering. The transformer does not explicitly predict bonds or order fragments; it generates a SMILES string representation.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10_1021_acscentsci_4c01132",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "molecular-fragment-assembly-from-transformer-predictions",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools[0].role",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "decoding stage for assembling molecular fragments into connectivity; learns attention-based mapping from spectral features to bond predictions and fragment ordering",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T10:02:55.256980+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/molecular-fragment-assembly-from-transformer-predictions/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "During training, we passed the processed 1H NMR spectra through a one-dimensional convolutional neural network (CNN) to downsample the signal into a lower-dimensional space.",
      "asbval:note": "CNN is explicitly used for spectral feature extraction.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10_1021_acscentsci_4c01132",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "molecular-fragment-assembly-from-transformer-predictions",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools[1].name",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "convolutional neural network",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T10:02:55.256980+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/molecular-fragment-assembly-from-transformer-predictions/005",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "During training, we passed the processed 1H NMR spectra through a one-dimensional convolutional neural network (CNN) to downsample the signal into a lower-dimensional space. For the processed 13C NMR spectra, since it is a binary vector, we embedded it into a dense vector representation. If both spectra were being used as input to the spectrum-to-structure model, then their features were concatenated... These features were then passed through a full encoder-decoder transformer for structure elucidation",
      "asbval:note": "CNN role as encoder for spectral feature extraction is accurately described.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10_1021_acscentsci_4c01132",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "molecular-fragment-assembly-from-transformer-predictions",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools[1].role",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "encoder stage; extracts spectral features from raw 1D NMR spectra prior to transformer decoding",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T10:02:55.256980+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/molecular-fragment-assembly-from-transformer-predictions/006",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
