    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/molecular-structure-prediction-evaluation/006",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "These features were then passed through a full encoder-decoder transformer for structure elucidation, which outputs SMILES strings, and a transformer encoder for substructure elucidation, which outputs substructure probability arrays... Autoregressive transformer models have been shown to excel at translation tasks owing to the strong inductive bias provided by the multihead attention mechanism, which captures global correlations and uses that information to generate the target sequence in a conditioned manner.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper uses encoder-decoder transformer to generate SMILES strings (molecular structures) from spectral features.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10_1021_acscentsci_4c01132",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "molecular-structure-prediction-evaluation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "transformer architecture - assembles molecular fragments (decoded from CNN features) into candidate molecular structures using attention mechanisms",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T10:03:28.698864+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/molecular-structure-prediction-evaluation/007",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Our framework uses an end-to-end approach... The top row of Figure 1 illustrates our full end-to-end multitask structure elucidation model, which takes in the 1H and/or 13C NMR spectra and predicts both the substructures in the molecule and the molecule's structure.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper describes the framework as a 'multitask structure elucidation model' or 'spectrum-to-structure multitask model', not explicitly named 'NMR2Struct'. The framework does combine CNN and transformer as claimed, but the specific tool name 'NMR2Struct' is not used in the paper.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10_1021_acscentsci_4c01132",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "molecular-structure-prediction-evaluation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "NMR2Struct model - end-to-end multitask framework combining CNN encoder and transformer fragment assembler for structure prediction from 1D NMR",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T10:03:28.698864+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/molecular-structure-prediction-out-of-distribution/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "we demonstrate the effectiveness of this framework on molecules with up to 19 heavy atoms, a size for which there are trillions of possible structures",
      "asbval:note": "Paper trains and evaluates the model on molecules UP TO 19 heavy atoms (not exceeding). The paper does NOT perform out-of-distribution evaluation on molecules >19 heavy atoms. The paper mentions that accuracy drops below 80% for 18-19 heavy atoms and notes this is likely due to training data imbalance (only 1% of training data from 18-19 atom molecules), but does not systematically extend evaluation beyond 19 atoms. The card claims an extension task that the paper does not perform.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10_1021_acscentsci_4c01132",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "molecular-structure-prediction-out-of-distribution",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Extend and evaluate a trained NMR2Struct deep learning model (transformer + CNN) on molecules exceeding its training scope (>19 heavy atoms)",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T10:03:48.244863+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/molecular-structure-prediction-out-of-distribution/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "the accuracy drops below 80% for the molecules with 18 or 19 heavy atoms. Although this sudden decrease could be explained in part by the problem size entering the trillions for molecules of that size, a more likely explanation might be that GDB-17 only contains molecules with up to 17 heavy atoms",
      "asbval:note": "Paper observes accuracy degradation at the boundary (18-19 atoms) and discusses failure modes (Tanimoto similarity analysis), but does not systematically characterize degradation BEYOND 19 atoms. The characterization is limited to the training boundary, not out-of-distribution extension.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10_1021_acscentsci_4c01132",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "molecular-structure-prediction-out-of-distribution",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "characterize accuracy degradation and failure modes in out-of-distribution settings",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
